# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ceramics-materials
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Corundum is the most common naturally occurring crystalline form of aluminium oxide.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Rubies and sapphires are gem-quality forms of corundum, which owe their characteristic colours to trace impurities.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Rubies are given their characteristic deep red colour and their laser qualities by traces of chromium.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Sapphires come in different colours given by various other impurities, such as iron and titanium.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] An extremely rare delta form occurs as the mineral deltalumite.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Although aluminium is the most abundant metal in the Earth's crust, it must be extracted from bauxite as alumina to produce aluminium metal.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The field of aluminium oxide ceramics has a long history.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium salts were widely used in ancient and medieval alchemy.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Several vintage textbooks cover the history of the field.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Al2O3 is an electrical insulator but has a relatively high thermal conductivity (30 Wm−1K−1) for a ceramic material.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] In its most commonly occurring crystalline form, called corundum or α-aluminium oxide, its hardness makes it suitable for use as an abrasive and as a component in cutting tools.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide is responsible for the resistance of metallic aluminium to weathering.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Metallic aluminium is very reactive with atmospheric oxygen, and a thin passivation layer of aluminium oxide (~5 nm thickness) forms on any exposed aluminium surface almost instantly.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] This layer protects the metal from further oxidation.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The thickness and properties of this oxide layer can be enhanced using a process called anodising.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] A number of alloys, such as aluminium bronzes, exploit this property by including a proportion of aluminium in the alloy to enhance corrosion resistance.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The aluminium oxide generated by anodising is typically amorphous, but discharge-assisted oxidation processes such as plasma electrolytic oxidation result in a significant proportion of crystalline aluminium oxide in the coating, enhancing its hardness.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide was taken off the United States Environmental Protection Agency's chemicals lists in 1988.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide is on the EPA's Toxics Release Inventory list if it is a fibrous form.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide is an amphoteric substance, meaning it can react with both acids and bases, such as hydrofluoric acid and sodium hydroxide, acting as an acid with a base and a base with an acid, neutralising the other and producing a salt.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The most common form of crystalline aluminium oxide is known as corundum, which is the thermodynamically stable form.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The oxygen ions form a nearly hexagonal close-packed structure with the aluminium ions filling two-thirds of the octahedral interstices.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] In terms of its crystallography, corundum adopts a trigonal Bravais lattice with a space group of R3c (number 167 in the International Tables).
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The primitive cell contains two formula units of aluminium oxide.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide also exists in other metastable phases, including the cubic γ and η phases, the monoclinic λ, θ, θ', and θ″ phase, the hexagonal χ phase, the orthorhombic κ phase the orthorhombic δ phase and the δ' tetragonal phase.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Each has a unique crystal structure and properties.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Cubic γ-Al2O3 has important technical applications.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The so-called β-Al2O3 proved to be NaAl11O17.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Molten aluminium oxide near the melting temperature is roughly 2/3 tetrahedral (i.e.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] 2/3 of the Al are surrounded by 4 oxygen neighbors), and 1/3 5-coordinated, with very little (<5%) octahedral Al-O present.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Around 80% of the oxygen atoms are shared among three or more Al-O polyhedra, and the majority of inter-polyhedral connections are corner-sharing, with the remaining 10–20% being edge-sharing.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The breakdown of octahedra upon melting is accompanied by a relatively large volume increase (~33%), the density of the liquid close to its melting point is 2.93 g/cm3.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The structure of molten alumina is temperature dependent and the fraction of 5- and 6-fold aluminium increases during cooling (and supercooling), at the expense of tetrahedral AlO4 units, approaching the local structural arrangements found in amorphous alumina.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium hydroxide minerals are the main component of bauxite, the principal ore of aluminium.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] A mixture of the minerals comprise bauxite ore, including gibbsite (Al(OH)3), boehmite (γ-AlO(OH)), and diaspore (α-AlO(OH)), along with impurities of iron oxides and hydroxides, quartz and clay minerals.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Except for SiO2, the other components of bauxite do not dissolve in base.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Upon filtering the basic mixture, Fe2O3 is removed.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] When the Bayer liquor is cooled, Al(OH)3 precipitates, leaving the silicates in solution.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The product aluminium oxide tends to be multi-phase, i.e., consisting of several phases of aluminium oxide rather than solely corundum.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The production process can therefore be optimized to produce a tailored product.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The type of phases present affects, for example, the solubility and pore structure of the aluminium oxide product which, in turn, affects the cost of aluminium production and pollution control.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The Sintering Process is a high-temperature method primarily used when the Bayer Process is not suitable, especially for ores with high silica content or when a more controlled product morphology is required.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Firstly, Bauxite is mixed with additives like limestone and soda ash, then heating the mixture at high temperatures (1200 °C to 1500 °C) to form sodium aluminate and calcium silicate.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] After sintering, the material is leached with water to dissolve the sodium aluminate, leaving behind impurities.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Sodium aluminate is then precipitated from the solution and calcined at around 1000 °C to produce alumina.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] This method is useful for the production of complex shapes and can be used to create porous or dense materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Known as *alpha alumina* in materials science, and as *alundum* (in fused form) or *aloxite* in mining and ceramic communities, aluminium oxide finds wide use.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Annual global production of aluminium oxide in 2015 was approximately 115 million tonnes, over 90% of which was used in the manufacture of aluminium metal.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The major uses of speciality aluminium oxides are in refractories, ceramics, polishing and abrasive applications.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Large tonnages of aluminium hydroxide, from which alumina is derived, are used in the manufacture of zeolites, coating titania pigments, and as a fire retardant/smoke suppressant.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Over 90% of aluminium oxide, termed *smelter grade alumina* (SGA), is consumed for the production of aluminium, usually by the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The remainder, termed *specialty alumina*, is used in a wide variety of applications which take advantage of its inertness, temperature resistance and electrical resistance.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Being fairly chemically inert and white, aluminium oxide is commonly used as a filler for plastics.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide is a common ingredient in sunscreen and is often also present in cosmetics such as blush, lipstick, and nail polish.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Many formulations of glass have aluminium oxide as an ingredient.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminosilicate glass is a commonly used type of glass that often contains 5% to 10% alumina.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide catalyses a variety of reactions that are useful industrially.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] In its largest scale application, aluminium oxide is the catalyst in the Claus process for converting hydrogen sulfide waste gases into elemental sulfur in refineries.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] It is also useful for dehydration of alcohols to alkenes.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide serves as a catalyst support for many industrial catalysts, such as those used in hydrodesulfurization and some Ziegler–Natta polymerizations.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide is widely used to remove water from gas streams.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide is used for its hardness and strength.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Its naturally occurring form, corundum, is a 9 on the Mohs scale of mineral hardness (just below diamond).
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] It is widely used as an abrasive, including as a much less expensive substitute for industrial diamond.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Many types of sandpaper use aluminium oxide crystals.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] In addition, its low heat retention and low specific heat make it widely used in grinding operations, particularly cutoff tools.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] As the powdery abrasive mineral aloxite, it is a major component, along with silica, of the cue tip "chalk" used in billiards.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide powder is used in some CD/DVD polishing and scratch-repair kits.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Its polishing qualities are also behind its use in toothpaste.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] It is also used in microdermabrasion, both in the machine process available through dermatologists and estheticians, and as a manual dermal abrasive used according to manufacturer directions.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide flakes are used in paint for reflective decorative effects, such as in the automotive or cosmetic industries.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide is a representative of bioinert ceramics.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Due to its excellent biocompatibility, high strength, and wear resistance, alumina ceramics are used in medical applications to manufacture artificial bones and joints.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] In this case, aluminium oxide is used to coat the surfaces of medical implants to give biocompatibility and corrosion resistance.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] It is also used for manufacturing dental implants, joint replacements, and other medical devices.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide has been used in a few experimental and commercial fiber materials for high-performance applications (e.g., Fiber FP, Nextel 610, Nextel 720).
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Alumina nanofibers in particular have become a research field of interest.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Some body armor utilizes alumina ceramic plates, usually in combination with aramid or UHMWPE backing to achieve effectiveness against most rifle threats.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Alumina ceramic armor is readily available to most civilians in jurisdictions where it is legal, but it is not considered military grade.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] An aluminium oxide layer can be grown as a protective coating on aluminium by anodizing or by plasma electrolytic oxidation (see the "Properties" above).
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Alumina is used to manufacture tiles which are attached inside pulverized fuel lines and flue gas ducting on coal fired power stations to protect high wear areas.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] They are not suitable for areas with high impact forces as these tiles are brittle and susceptible to breakage.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The Al2O3 films prepared using O3 show 10–100 times lower leakage current density compared with those prepared by H2O.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide, being a dielectric with relatively large band gap, is used as an insulating barrier in capacitors.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium ice cream scoops, if improperly washed by using a dishwasher rather than washed by hand, can corrode and leave an aluminium oxide residue, which can present a health concern.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] In lighting, translucent aluminium oxide is used in some sodium vapor lamps.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide is also used in preparation of coating suspensions in compact fluorescent lamps.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] In chemistry laboratories, aluminium oxide is a medium for chromatography, available in basic (pH 9.5), acidic (pH 4.5 when in water), and neutral formulations.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Additionally, small pieces of aluminium oxide are often used as boiling chips.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Health and medical applications include it as a material in hip replacements and birth-control pills.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] It is used as a scintillator and dosimeter for radiation protection and therapy applications for its optically stimulated luminescence properties.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Insulation for high-temperature furnaces is often manufactured from aluminium oxide.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Sometimes the insulation contains a percentage of silica depending on the temperature rating of the material.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] The insulation can be made in blanket, board, brick, and loose fiber forms for various application requirements.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] It is also used to make spark-plug insulators.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Using a plasma-spray process and mixed with titania, it is coated onto the braking surface of some bicycle rims to provide abrasion and wear resistance.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Most ceramic eyes on fishing rods are circular rings made from aluminium oxide.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] In its finest powdered (white) form, called diamantine, aluminium oxide is used as a superior polishing abrasive in watchmaking and clockmaking.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] Aluminium oxide is also used in the coating of stanchions in the motocross and mountain-bike industries.
[src:ceramics-materials/alumina] This coating is combined with molybdenum disulfide to provide long-term lubrication of the surface.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] A **ceramic** is any of the various hard, brittle, heat-resistant, and corrosion-resistant materials made by shaping and then firing an inorganic, nonmetallic material, such as clay, at a high temperature.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Common examples are earthenware, porcelain, and brick.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The earliest ceramics made by humans were fired clay bricks used for building house walls and other structures.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Other pottery objects such as pots, vessels, vases and figurines were made from clay, either by itself or mixed with other materials like silica, hardened by sintering in fire.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Later, ceramics were glazed and fired to create smooth, colored surfaces, decreasing porosity through the use of glassy, amorphous ceramic coatings on top of the crystalline ceramic substrates.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramics now include domestic, industrial, and building products, as well as a wide range of materials developed for use in advanced ceramic engineering, such as semiconductors.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The word *ceramic* comes from the Ancient Greek word κεραμικός (*keramikós*), meaning "of or for pottery" (from κέραμος*(*kéramos*)* 'potter's clay, tile, pottery').
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The earliest known mention of the root *ceram-* is the Mycenaean Greek *ke-ra-me-we*, workers of ceramic, written in Linear B syllabic script.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The word *ceramic* can be used as an adjective to describe a material, product, or process, or it may be used as a noun, either singular or, more commonly, as the plural noun *ceramics*.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramic material is an inorganic, metallic oxide, nitride, or carbide material.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Some elements, such as carbon or silicon, may be considered ceramics.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramic materials are brittle, hard, strong in compression, and weak in shearing and tension.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] They withstand the chemical erosion that occurs in other materials subjected to acidic or caustic environments.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramics generally can withstand very high temperatures, ranging from 1,000 °C to 1,600 °C (1,800 °F to 3,000 °F).
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The crystallinity of ceramic materials varies widely.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Most often, fired ceramics are either vitrified or semi-vitrified, as is the case with earthenware, stoneware, and porcelain.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Varying crystallinity and electron composition in the ionic and covalent bonds cause most ceramic materials to be good thermal and electrical insulators (researched in ceramic engineering).
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Composites such as fiberglass and carbon fiber, while containing ceramic materials, are not considered to be part of the ceramic family.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Highly oriented crystalline ceramic materials are not amenable to a great range of processing.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Methods for dealing with them tend to fall into one of two categories: either making the ceramic in the desired shape by reaction *in situ* or "forming" powders into the desired shape and then sintering to form a solid body.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramic forming techniques include shaping by hand (sometimes including a rotation process called "throwing"), slip casting, tape casting (used for making very thin ceramic capacitors), injection molding, dry pressing, and other variations.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Many ceramics experts do not consider materials with an amorphous (noncrystalline) character (i.e., glass) to be ceramics, even though glassmaking involves several steps of the ceramic process and its mechanical properties are similar to those of ceramic materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] However, heat treatments can convert glass into a semi-crystalline material known as glass-ceramic.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Traditional ceramic raw materials include clay minerals such as kaolinite, whereas more recent materials include aluminium oxide, more commonly known as alumina.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Modern ceramic materials, which are classified as advanced ceramics, include silicon carbide and tungsten carbide.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Both are valued for their abrasion resistance and are therefore used in applications such as the wear plates of crushing equipment in mining operations.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Advanced ceramics are also used in the medical, electrical, electronics, and armor industries.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Human beings appear to have been making their own ceramics for at least 26,000 years, subjecting clay and silica to intense heat to fuse and form ceramic materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The earliest found so far were in southern central Europe and were sculpted figures, not dishes.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The earliest known pottery was made by mixing animal products with clay and firing it at up to 800 °C (1,500 °F).
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] While pottery fragments have been found up to 19,000 years old, it was not until about 10,000 years later that regular pottery became common.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] An early people that spread across much of Europe is named after its use of pottery: the Corded Ware culture.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] These early Indo-European peoples decorated their pottery by wrapping it with rope while it was still wet.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] When the ceramics were fired, the rope burned off but left a decorative pattern of complex grooves on the surface.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The invention of the wheel eventually led to the production of smoother, more even pottery using the wheel-forming (throwing) technique, like the pottery wheel.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Early ceramics were porous, absorbing water easily.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] It became useful for more items with the discovery of glazing techniques, which involved coating pottery with silicon, bone ash, or other materials that could melt and reform into a glassy surface, making a vessel less pervious to water.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramic artifacts have an important role in archaeology for understanding the culture, technology, and behavior of peoples of the past.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] They are among the most common artifacts to be found at an archaeological site, generally in the form of small fragments of broken pottery called sherds.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The processing of collected sherds can be consistent with two main types of analysis: technical and traditional.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The traditional analysis involves sorting ceramic artifacts, sherds, and larger fragments into specific types based on style, composition, manufacturing, and morphology.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] By creating these typologies, it is possible to distinguish between different cultural styles, the purpose of the ceramic, and the technological state of the people, among other conclusions.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Besides, by looking at stylistic changes in ceramics over time, it is possible to separate (seriate) the ceramics into distinct diagnostic groups (assemblages).
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] A comparison of ceramic artifacts with known dated assemblages allows for a chronological assignment of these pieces.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The technical approach to ceramic analysis involves a finer examination of the composition of ceramic artifacts and sherds to determine the source of the material and, through this, the possible manufacturing site.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Key criteria are the composition of the clay and the temper used in the manufacture of the article under study: the temper is a material added to the clay during the initial production stage and is used to aid the subsequent drying process.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Types of temper include shell pieces, granite fragments, and ground sherd pieces called 'grog'.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Temper is usually identified by microscopic examination of the tempered material.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Clay identification is determined by a process of refiring the ceramic and assigning a color to it using Munsell Soil Color notation.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] By estimating both the clay and temper compositions and locating a region where both are known to occur, an assignment of the material source can be made.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Based on the source assignment of the artifact, further investigations can be made into the site of manufacture.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The physical properties of any ceramic substance are a direct result of its crystalline structure and chemical composition.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramography is the art and science of preparation, examination, and evaluation of ceramic microstructures.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Evaluation and characterization of ceramic microstructures are often implemented on similar spatial scales to that used commonly in the emerging field of nanotechnology: from nanometers to tens of micrometers (μm).
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] This is typically somewhere between the minimum wavelength of visible light and the resolution limit of the naked eye.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The microstructure includes most grains, secondary phases, grain boundaries, pores, micro-cracks, structural defects, and hardness micro indentions.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Most bulk mechanical, optical, thermal, electrical, and magnetic properties are significantly affected by the observed microstructure.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The fabrication method and process conditions are generally indicated by the microstructure.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The root cause of many ceramic failures is evident in the cleaved and polished microstructure.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Mechanical properties are important in structural and building materials as well as textile fabrics.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] In modern materials science, fracture mechanics is an important tool in improving the mechanical performance of materials and components.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] It applies the physics of stress and strain, in particular the theories of elasticity and plasticity, to the microscopic crystallographic defects found in real materials in order to predict the macroscopic mechanical failure of bodies.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Fractography is widely used with fracture mechanics to understand the causes of failures and also verify the theoretical failure predictions with real-life failures.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramic materials are usually ionic or covalent bonded materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] A material held together by either type of bond will tend to fracture before any plastic deformation takes place, which results in poor toughness and brittle behavior in these materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Additionally, because these materials tend to be porous, pores and other microscopic imperfections act as stress concentrators, decreasing the toughness further, and reducing the tensile strength.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] These combine to give catastrophic failures, as opposed to the more ductile failure modes of metals.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] These materials do show plastic deformation.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] However, because of the rigid structure of crystalline material, there are very few available slip systems for dislocations to move, and so they deform very slowly.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] To overcome the brittle behavior, ceramic material development has introduced the class of ceramic matrix composite materials, in which ceramic fibers are embedded and with specific coatings form fiber bridges across any crack.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] This mechanism substantially increases the fracture toughness of such ceramics.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramic disc brakes are an example of using a ceramic matrix composite material manufactured with a specific process.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Scientists are working on developing ceramic materials that can withstand significant deformation without breaking.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] A first such material that can deform in room temperature was found in 2024.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Many strategies are employed to improve the toughness of ceramics to prevent fracture.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] This includes crack deflection, microcrack toughening, crack bridging, incorporation of ductile particles, and transformation toughening.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Crack deflection is a toughening mechanism that involves deflecting cracks away from more rapid crack propagation paths, preventing catastrophic sudden failure.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Cracks may be deflected using microstructures such as whiskers, as in the use of silicon carbide whiskers to reinforce molybdenum disilicide ceramic material detailed in a 1987 paper.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Crack deflecting second phases may also take the form of platelets, particles, or fibers.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Microcrack toughening involves nucleation (creation) of microcracks near a macroscopic crack tip where the crack propagates, which lowers the stress experienced by the tip and therefore the urgency of crack propagation.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] To improve toughness, second phase particles can be incorporated into ceramic such that they are subject to microcracking, which relieves stress to prevent fracture.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Crack bridging occurs when a strong discontinuous reinforcing phase applies a force behind the propagating tip of the crack that discourages further cracking.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] These second phase bridges essentially pin the crack to discourage its extension.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Crack bridging can be used to improve toughness via the incorporation of second phase whiskers in the ceramic, as well as other shapes, to bridge cracks.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ductile particle ceramic matrix composites are composed of ductile particles such as metals distributed in a ceramic matrix.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] These particles boost toughness by deforming plastically to absorb energy, and by bridging advancing cracks.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] To be most effective, the particles should be isolated from each other.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The most studied iterations of these composites consist of an alumina matrix, and nickel, iron, molybdenum, copper, or silver metal particles.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Transformation toughening occurs when a material undergoes stress-induced phase transformation.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Some ceramics are capable of undergoing stress-induced martensitic transformation, which involves an energy barrier that must be overcome by absorbing energy.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Martensitic transformations are diffusionless shear transformations involving the transition between an "austenite" or "parent" phase that is stable at higher temperatures and a "martensitic" phase that is stable at lower temperatures.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Because the transformation absorbs energy, stress-induced martensitic transformations can hinder crack progression and increases toughness.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] A key example of this phenomenon is zirconia, whose martensitic transformation involves a crystal structure transformation from a tetragonal crystal structure (the austenite phase) to a monoclinic structure.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The volume increase associated with transformation from tetragonal to monoclinic also relieves tensile stress at the crack, tip, further discouraging cracking and increasing toughness.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] When zirconia particles in a ceramic matrix undergo transformation during fabrication due to cooling, the stress fields around the particles lead to nucleation and extension of microcracks, which can also improve toughness of the material.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] These stress fields, as well as the particles themselves, can also contribute to crack deflection.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] If a ceramic is subjected to substantial mechanical loading, it can undergo a process called ice-templating, which allows some control of the microstructure of the ceramic product and therefore some control of the mechanical properties.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramic engineers use this technique to tune the mechanical properties to their desired application.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Specifically, the strength is increased when this technique is employed.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ice templating allows the creation of macroscopic pores in a unidirectional arrangement.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The applications of this oxide strengthening technique are important for solid oxide fuel cells and water filtration devices.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] To process a sample through ice templating, an aqueous colloidal suspension is prepared to contain the dissolved ceramic powder evenly dispersed throughout the colloid, for example yttria-stabilized zirconia (YSZ).
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The solution is then cooled from the bottom to the top on a platform that allows for unidirectional cooling.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The sample is then heated and at the same the pressure is reduced enough to force the ice crystals to sublime and the YSZ pockets begin to anneal together to form macroscopically aligned ceramic microstructures.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The sample is then further sintered to complete the evaporation of the residual water and the final consolidation of the ceramic microstructure.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] During ice-templating, a few variables can be controlled to influence the pore size and morphology of the microstructure.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] These important variables are the initial solids loading of the colloid, the cooling rate, the sintering temperature and duration, and the use of certain additives which can influence the microstructural morphology during the process.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] A good understanding of these parameters is essential to understanding the relationships between processing, microstructure, and mechanical properties of anisotropically porous materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Most of these are transition metal oxides that are II-VI semiconductors, such as zinc oxide.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] While there are prospects of mass-producing blue light-emitting diodes (LED) from zinc oxide, ceramicists are most interested in the electrical properties that show grain boundary effects.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] One of the most widely used of these is the varistor.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] These are devices that exhibit the property that resistance drops sharply at a certain threshold voltage.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Once the voltage across the device reaches the threshold, there is a breakdown of the electrical structure in the vicinity of the grain boundaries, which results in its electrical resistance dropping from several megohms down to a few hundred ohms.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The major advantage of these is that they can dissipate a lot of energy, and they self-reset; after the voltage across the device drops below the threshold, its resistance returns to being high.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] This makes them ideal for surge-protection applications; as there is control over the threshold voltage and energy tolerance, they find use in all sorts of applications.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The best demonstration of their ability can be found in electrical substations, where they are employed to protect the infrastructure from lightning strikes.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] They have rapid response, are low maintenance, and do not appreciably degrade from use, making them virtually ideal devices for this application.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Semiconducting ceramics are also employed as gas sensors.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] When various gases are passed over a polycrystalline ceramic, its electrical resistance changes.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] With tuning to the possible gas mixtures, very inexpensive devices can be produced.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Under some conditions, such as extremely low temperatures, some ceramics exhibit high-temperature superconductivity (in superconductivity, "high temperature" means above 30 K).
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The reason for this is not understood, but there are two major families of superconducting ceramics.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Piezoelectricity, a link between electrical and mechanical response, is exhibited by a large number of ceramic materials, including the quartz used to measure time in watches and other electronics.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Such devices use both properties of piezoelectrics, using electricity to produce a mechanical motion (powering the device) and then using this mechanical motion to produce electricity (generating a signal).
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The unit of time measured is the natural interval required for electricity to be converted into mechanical energy and back again.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The piezoelectric effect is generally stronger in materials that also exhibit pyroelectricity, and all pyroelectric materials are also piezoelectric.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] These materials can be used to inter-convert between thermal, mechanical, or electrical energy; for instance, after synthesis in a furnace, a pyroelectric crystal allowed to cool under no applied stress generally builds up a static charge of thousands of volts.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Such materials are used in motion sensors, where the tiny rise in temperature from a warm body entering the room is enough to produce a measurable voltage in the crystal.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] In turn, pyroelectricity is seen most strongly in materials that also display the ferroelectric effect, in which a stable electric dipole can be oriented or reversed by applying an electrostatic field.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Pyroelectricity is also a necessary consequence of ferroelectricity.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] This can be used to store information in ferroelectric capacitors, elements of ferroelectric RAM.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The most common such materials are lead zirconate titanate and barium titanate.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Aside from the uses mentioned above, their strong piezoelectric response is exploited in the design of high-frequency loudspeakers, transducers for sonar, and actuators for atomic force and scanning tunneling microscopes.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Temperature increases can cause grain boundaries to suddenly become insulating in some semiconducting ceramic materials, mostly mixtures of heavy metal titanates.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The critical transition temperature can be adjusted over a wide range by variations in chemistry.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] In such materials, current will pass through the material until joule heating brings it to the transition temperature, at which point the circuit will be broken and current flow will cease.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Such ceramics are used as self-controlled heating elements in, for example, the rear-window defrost circuits of automobiles.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] At the transition temperature, the material's dielectric response becomes theoretically infinite.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] While a lack of temperature control would rule out any practical use of the material near its critical temperature, the dielectric effect remains exceptionally strong even at much higher temperatures.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Titanates with critical temperatures far below room temperature have become synonymous with "ceramic" in the context of ceramic capacitors for just this reason.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Optically transparent materials focus on the response of a material to incoming light waves of a range of wavelengths.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Frequency selective optical filters can be utilized to alter or enhance the brightness and contrast of a digital image.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] This resonant mode of energy and data transmission via electromagnetic (light) wave propagation, though low powered, is virtually lossless.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Optical waveguides are used as components in Integrated optical circuits (e.g. light-emitting diodes, LEDs) or as the transmission medium in local and long haul optical communication systems.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Also of value to the emerging materials scientist is the sensitivity of materials to radiation in the thermal infrared (IR) portion of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] This heat-seeking ability is responsible for such diverse optical phenomena as night-vision and IR luminescence.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Thus, there is an increasing need in the military sector for high-strength, robust materials which have the capability to transmit light (electromagnetic waves) in the visible (0.4 – 0.7 micrometers) and mid-infrared (1 – 5 micrometers) regions of the spectrum.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] These materials are needed for applications requiring transparent armor, including next-generation high-speed missiles and pods, as well as protection against improvised explosive devices (IED).
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] In the 1960s, scientists at General Electric (GE) discovered that under the right manufacturing conditions, some ceramics, especially aluminium oxide (alumina), could be made translucent.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] These translucent materials were transparent enough to be used for containing the electrical plasma generated in high-pressure sodium street lamps.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] During the past two decades, additional types of transparent ceramics have been developed for applications such as nose cones for heat-seeking missiles, windows for fighter aircraft, and scintillation counters for computed tomography scanners.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Sialon (silicon aluminium oxynitride) has high strength, resistance to thermal shock, chemical and wear resistance, and low density.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] These ceramics are used in non-ferrous molten metal handling, weld pins, and the chemical industry.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Silicon carbide (SiC) is used as a susceptor in microwave furnaces, a commonly used abrasive, and as a refractory material.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Silicon nitride (Si3N4) is used as an abrasive powder.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Steatite (magnesium silicates) is used as an electrical insulator.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Titanium carbide is used in space shuttle re-entry shields and scratchproof watches.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Uranium oxide (UO2) is used as fuel in nuclear reactors.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Yttrium barium copper oxide (YBa2Cu3O7−x) is a high-temperature superconductor.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Zinc oxide (ZnO) is a semiconductor used in the construction of varistors.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Zirconium dioxide (zirconia), which in pure form undergoes many phase changes between room temperature and practical sintering temperatures, can be chemically "stabilized" in several different forms.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Its high oxygen ion conductivity recommends it for use in fuel cells and automotive oxygen sensors.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] In another variant, metastable structures can impart transformation toughening for mechanical applications; most ceramic knife blades are made of this material.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Partially stabilised zirconia (PSZ) is much less brittle than other ceramics and is used for metal forming tools, valves and liners, abrasive slurries, kitchen knives and bearings subject to severe abrasion.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Technical, also known as engineering, advanced, special, and fine ceramics.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Frequently, the raw materials of modern ceramics do not include clays.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Composite materials**:** particulate reinforced, fiber reinforced, combinations of oxides and non-oxides.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Each one of these classes can be developed into unique material properties.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Carbon–ceramic brake disks for vehicles: highly resistant to brake fade at high temperatures.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Advanced composite ceramic and metal matrices have been designed for most modern armoured fighting vehicles because they offer superior penetrating resistance against shaped charge (HEAT rounds) and kinetic energy penetrators.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramics such as alumina and boron carbide have been used as plates in ballistic armored vests to repel high-velocity rifle fire.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Such plates are known commonly as small arms protective inserts, or SAPIs.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Similar low-weight material is used to protect the cockpits of some military aircraft.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramic ball bearings can be used in place of steel.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Their greater hardness results in lower susceptibility to wear.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramic bearings typically last triple the lifetime of steel bearings.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] They deform less than steel under load, resulting in less contact with the bearing retainer walls and lower friction.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] In very high-speed applications, heat from friction causes more problems for metal bearings than ceramic bearings.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramics are chemically resistant to corrosion and are preferred for environments where steel bearings would rust.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] In some applications their electricity-insulating properties are advantageous.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Drawbacks to ceramic bearings include significantly higher cost, susceptibility to damage under shock loads, and the potential to wear steel parts due to ceramics' greater hardness.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] In the early 1980s Toyota researched production of an adiabatic engine using ceramic components in the hot gas area.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The use of ceramics would have allowed temperatures exceeding 1650 °C.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Advantages would include lighter materials and a smaller cooling system (or no cooling system at all), leading to major weight reduction.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The expected increase of fuel efficiency (due to higher operating temperatures, demonstrated in Carnot's theorem) could not be verified experimentally.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] It was found that heat transfer on the hot ceramic cylinder wall was greater than the heat transfer to a cooler metal wall.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] This is because the cooler gas film on a metal surface acts as a thermal insulator.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Thus, despite the desirable properties of ceramics, prohibitive production costs and limited advantages have prevented widespread ceramic engine component adoption.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] In addition, small imperfections in ceramic material along with low fracture toughness can lead to cracking and potentially dangerous equipment failure.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Such engines are possible experimentally, but mass production is not feasible with current technology.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Experiments with ceramic parts for gas turbine engines are being conducted.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Currently, even blades made of advanced metal alloys used in the engines' hot section require cooling and careful monitoring of operating temperatures.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Turbine engines made with ceramics could operate more efficiently, providing for greater range and payload.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Recent advances have been made in ceramics which include bioceramics such as dental implants and synthetic bones.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Hydroxyapatite, the major mineral component of bone, has been made synthetically from several biological and chemical components and can be formed into ceramic materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Orthopedic implants coated with these materials bond readily to bone and other tissues in the body without rejection or inflammatory reaction.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] They are of great interest for gene delivery and tissue engineering scaffolding.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Most hydroxyapatite ceramics are quite porous and lack mechanical strength and are therefore used solely to coat metal orthopedic devices to aid in forming a bond to bone or as bone fillers.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] They are also used as fillers for orthopedic plastic screws to aid in reducing inflammation and increase the absorption of these plastic materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Work is being done to make strong, fully dense nanocrystalline hydroxyapatite ceramic materials for orthopedic weight bearing devices, replacing foreign metal and plastic orthopedic materials with a synthetic but naturally occurring bone mineral.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ultimately, these ceramic materials may be used as bone replacement, or with the incorporation of protein collagens, the manufacture of synthetic bones.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Applications for actinide-containing ceramic materials include nuclear fuels for burning excess plutonium (Pu), or a chemically inert source of alpha radiation in power supplies for uncrewed space vehicles or microelectronic devices.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Use and disposal of radioactive actinides require immobilization in a durable host material.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Long half-life radionuclides such as actinide are immobilized using chemically durable crystalline materials based on polycrystalline ceramics and large single crystals.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] High-tech ceramics are used for producing watch cases.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] The material is valued by watchmakers for its light weight, scratch resistance, durability, and smooth touch.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] IWC is one of the brands that pioneered the use of ceramic in watchmaking.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramics are used in the design of mobile phone bodies due to their high hardness, resistance to scratches, and ability to dissipate heat.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramic's thermal management properties help in maintaining optimal device temperatures during heavy use enhancing performance.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Additionally, ceramic materials can support wireless charging and offer better signal transmission compared to metals, which can interfere with antennas.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Companies like Apple and Samsung have incorporated ceramic in their devices.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Ceramics made of silicon carbide are used in pump and valve components because of their corrosion resistance characteristics.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] It is also used in nuclear reactors as fuel cladding materials due to their ability to withstand radiation and thermal stress.
[src:ceramics-materials/ceramic] Other uses of Silicon carbide ceramics include paper manufacturing, ballistics, chemical production, and as pipe system components.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect results from the linear electromechanical interaction between the mechanical and electrical states in crystalline materials with no inversion symmetry.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect is a reversible process: materials exhibiting the piezoelectric effect also exhibit the reverse piezoelectric effect, the internal generation of a mechanical strain resulting from an applied electric field.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] For example, lead zirconate titanate crystals will generate measurable piezoelectricity when their static structure is deformed by about 0.1% of the original dimension.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Conversely, those same crystals will change about 0.1% of their static dimension when an external electric field is applied.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The inverse piezoelectric effect is used in the production of ultrasound waves.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] French physicists Jacques and Pierre Curie discovered piezoelectricity in 1880.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] It forms the basis for scanning probe microscopes that resolve images at the scale of atoms.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] It is used in the pickups of some electronically amplified guitars and as triggers in most modern electronic drums.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect also finds everyday uses, such as generating sparks to ignite gas cooking and heating devices, torches, and cigarette lighters.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The word *piezoelectricity* means electricity resulting from pressure.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] It is derived from Ancient Greek πιέζω*(*piézō*)* 'to squeeze or press' and ἤλεκτρον*(*ḗlektron*)* 'amber' (an ancient source of static electricity).
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The German form of the word (*Piezoelektrizität*) was coined in 1881 by the German physicist Wilhelm Gottlieb Hankel; the English word was derived from German in 1883.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The pyroelectric effect, by which a material generates an electric potential in response to a temperature change, was studied by Carl Linnaeus and Franz Aepinus in the mid-18th century.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Drawing on this knowledge, both René Just Haüy and Antoine César Becquerel posited a relationship between mechanical stress and electric charge; however, experiments by both proved inconclusive.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The first demonstration of the direct piezoelectric effect was in 1880 by the brothers Pierre Curie and Jacques Curie.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Quartz and Rochelle salt exhibited the most piezoelectricity.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The Curies, however, did not predict the converse piezoelectric effect.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The converse effect was mathematically deduced from fundamental thermodynamic principles by Gabriel Lippmann in 1881.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The Curies immediately confirmed the existence of the converse effect, and went on to obtain quantitative proof of the complete reversibility of electro-elasto-mechanical deformations in piezoelectric crystals.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] For the next few decades, piezoelectricity remained something of a laboratory curiosity, though it was a vital tool in the discovery of polonium and radium by Pierre and Marie Curie in 1898.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] More work was done to explore and define the crystal structures that exhibited piezoelectricity.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] This culminated in 1910 with the publication of Woldemar Voigt's *Lehrbuch der Kristallphysik* (*Textbook on Crystal Physics*), which described the 20 natural crystal classes capable of piezoelectricity, and rigorously defined the piezoelectric constants using tensor analysis.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The first practical application for piezoelectric devices was sonar, first developed during World War I.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The superior performance of piezoelectric devices, operating at ultrasonic frequencies, superseded the earlier Fessenden oscillator.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] In France in 1917, Paul Langevin and his coworkers developed an ultrasonic submarine detector.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The detector consisted of a transducer, made of thin quartz crystals carefully glued between two steel plates, and a hydrophone to detect the returned echo.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] By emitting a high-frequency pulse from the transducer, and measuring the amount of time it takes to hear an echo from the sound waves bouncing off an object, one can calculate the distance to that object.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric devices found homes in many fields.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Ceramic phonograph cartridges simplified player design, were cheap and accurate, and made record players cheaper to maintain and easier to build.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The development of the ultrasonic transducer allowed for easy measurement of viscosity and elasticity in fluids and solids, resulting in huge advances in materials research.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Ultrasonic time-domain reflectometers (which send an ultrasonic pulse through a material and measure reflections from discontinuities) could find flaws inside cast metal and stone objects, improving structural safety.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] During World War II, independent research groups in the United States, USSR, and Japan discovered a new class of synthetic materials, called ferroelectrics, which exhibited piezoelectric constants many times higher than natural materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] This led to intense research to develop barium titanate and later lead zirconate titanate materials with specific properties for particular applications.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] One significant example of the use of piezoelectric crystals was developed by Bell Telephone Laboratories.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Lack, working in radio telephony in the engineering department, developed the "AT cut" crystal, a crystal that operated through a wide range of temperatures.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Lack's crystal did not need the heavy accessories previous crystal used, facilitating its use on the aircraft.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] This development allowed Allied air forces to engage in coordinated mass attacks through the use of aviation radio.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Development of piezoelectric devices and materials in the United States was kept within the companies doing the development, mostly due to the wartime beginnings of the field, and in the interests of securing profitable patents.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] New materials were the first to be developed—quartz crystals were the first commercially exploited piezoelectric material, but scientists searched for higher-performance materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Despite the advances in materials and the maturation of manufacturing processes, the United States market did not grow as quickly as Japan's did.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Without many new applications, the growth of the United States' piezoelectric industry suffered.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] In contrast, Japanese manufacturers shared their information, quickly overcoming technical and manufacturing challenges and creating new markets.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] In Japan, a temperature stable crystal cut was developed by Issac Koga.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Japanese efforts in materials research created piezoceramic materials competitive to the United States materials but free of expensive patent restrictions.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Ultrasonic transducers that transmit sound waves through air had existed for quite some time but first saw major commercial use in early television remote controls.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] These transducers now are mounted on several car models as an echolocation device, helping the driver determine the distance from the car to any objects that may be in its path.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The nature of the piezoelectric effect is closely related to the occurrence of electric dipole moments in solids.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] These may be either induced for ions on crystal lattice sites with asymmetric charge surroundings (as in BaTiO3 and PZTs) or directly carried by molecular groups (as in cane sugar).
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The dipole density or polarization (dimensionality [C·m/m3] ) may easily be calculated for crystals by summing up the dipole moments per volume of the crystallographic unit cell.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] As every dipole is a vector, the dipole density ***P*** is a vector field.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Dipoles near each other tend to be aligned in regions called Weiss domains.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The domains are usually randomly oriented, but can be aligned using the process of *poling* (not the same as magnetic poling), a process by which a strong electric field is applied across the material, usually at elevated temperatures.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Not all piezoelectric materials can be poled.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Of importance for the piezoelectric effect is the change of polarization ***P*** when applying a mechanical stress.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] This might either be caused by a reconfiguration of the dipole-inducing surrounding or by re-orientation of molecular dipole moments under the influence of the external stress.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectricity may then manifest in a variation of the polarization strength, its direction or both, with the details depending on: 1. the orientation of ***P*** within the crystal; 2. crystal symmetry; and 3. the applied mechanical stress.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The change in ***P*** appears as a variation of surface charge density upon the crystal faces, i.e. as a variation of the electric field extending between the faces caused by a change in dipole density in the bulk.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] For example, a 1 cm3 cube of quartz with 2 kN (500 lbf) of correctly applied force can produce a voltage of 12500 V.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric materials also show the opposite effect, called the **converse piezoelectric effect**, where the application of an electrical field creates mechanical deformation in the crystal.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] where ${\mathfrak {d}}$ is the piezoelectric tensor and the superscript t stands for its transpose.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] where [*d*] is the matrix for the direct piezoelectric effect and [*d*t] is the matrix for the converse piezoelectric effect.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The superscript *E* indicates a zero, or constant, electric field; the superscript *T* indicates a zero, or constant, stress field; and the superscript t stands for transposition of a matrix.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Notice that the third order tensor ${\mathfrak {d}}$ maps vectors into symmetric matrices.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] There are no non-trivial rotation-invariant tensors that have this property, which is why there are no isotropic piezoelectric materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] where the first equation represents the relationship for the converse piezoelectric effect and the latter for the direct piezoelectric effect.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Although the above equations are the most used form in literature, some comments about the notation are necessary.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Generally, *D* and *E* are vectors, that is, Cartesian tensors of rank 1; and permittivity *ε* is a Cartesian tensor of rank 2.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Strain and stress are, in principle, also rank-2 tensors.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] But conventionally, because strain and stress are all symmetric tensors, the subscript of strain and stress can be relabeled in the following fashion: 11 → 1; 22 → 2; 33 → 3; 23 → 4; 13 → 5; 12 → 6.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] (Different conventions may be used by different authors in literature.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] For example, some use 12 → 4; 23 → 5; 31 → 6 instead.) That is why *S* and *T* appear to have the "vector form" of six components.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Consequently, *s* appears to be a 6-by-6 matrix instead of a rank-3 tensor.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Such a relabeled notation is often called Voigt notation.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Whether the shear strain components *S*4, *S*5, *S*6 are tensor components or engineering strains is another question.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] In the equation above, they must be engineering strains for the 6,6 coefficient of the compliance matrix to be written as shown, i.e., 2(*s**E* 11 − *s**E* 12).
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Engineering shear strains are double the value of the corresponding tensor shear, such as *S*6 = 2*S*12 and so on.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] This also means that *s*66 = ⁠1/*G*12⁠, where *G*12 is the shear modulus.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] where the first set of four terms corresponds to the direct piezoelectric effect and the second set of four terms corresponds to the converse piezoelectric effect.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The equality between the direct piezoelectric tensor and the transpose of the converse piezoelectric tensor originates from the Maxwell relations of thermodynamics.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] For those piezoelectric crystals for which the polarization is of the crystal-field induced type, a formalism has been worked out that allows for the calculation of piezoelectrical coefficients *dij* from electrostatic lattice constants or higher-order Madelung constants.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Of the 32 crystal classes, 21 are non-centrosymmetric (not having a centre of symmetry), and of these, 20 exhibit direct piezoelectricity (the 21st is the cubic class 432).
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Ten of these represent the polar crystal classes, which show a spontaneous polarization without mechanical stress due to a non-vanishing electric dipole moment associated with their unit cell, and which exhibit pyroelectricity.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] If the dipole moment can be reversed by applying an external electric field, the material is said to be ferroelectric.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] For polar crystals, for which ***P*** ≠ 0 holds without applying a mechanical load, the piezoelectric effect manifests itself by changing the magnitude or the direction of ***P*** or both.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] For the nonpolar but piezoelectric crystals, on the other hand, a polarization ***P*** different from zero is only elicited by applying a mechanical load.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] For them the stress can be imagined to transform the material from a nonpolar crystal class (***P*** = 0) to a polar one, having ***P*** ≠ 0.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Many materials exhibit piezoelectricity.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Ceramics with randomly oriented grains must be ferroelectric to exhibit piezoelectricity.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Macroscopic piezoelectricity is possible in textured polycrystalline non-ferroelectric piezoelectric materials, such as AlN and ZnO.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The fabrication of lead-free piezoceramics pose multiple challenges, from an environmental standpoint and their ability to replicate the properties of their lead-based counterparts.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] By removing the lead component of the piezoceramic, the risk of toxicity to humans decreases, but the mining and extraction of the materials can be harmful to the environment.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Most of the concerns with KNN, specifically its Nb2O5 component, are in the early phase of its life cycle before it reaches manufacturers.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Since the harmful impacts are focused on these early phases, some actions can be taken to minimize the effects.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Returning the land as close to its original form after Nb2O5 mining via dam deconstruction or replacing a stockpile of utilizable soil are known aids for any extraction event.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] For minimizing air quality effects, modeling and simulation still needs to occur to fully understand what mitigation methods are required.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The extraction of lead-free piezoceramic components has not grown to a significant scale at this time, but from early analysis, experts encourage caution when it comes to environmental effects.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Fabricating lead-free piezoceramics faces the challenge of maintaining the performance and stability of their lead-based counterparts.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] In general, the main fabrication challenge is creating the "morphotropic phase boundaries (MPBs)" that provide the materials with their stable piezoelectric properties without introducing the "polymorphic phase boundaries (PPBs)" that decrease the temperature stability of the material.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] New phase boundaries are created by varying additive concentrations so that the phase transition temperatures converge at room temperature.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The introduction of the MPB improves piezoelectric properties, but if a PPB is introduced, the material becomes negatively affected by temperature.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Research is ongoing to control the type of phase boundaries that are introduced through phase engineering, diffusing phase transitions, domain engineering, and chemical modification.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] A piezoelectric potential can be created in any bulk or nanostructured semiconductor crystal having non central symmetry, such as the Group III–V and II–VI materials, due to polarization of ions under applied stress and strain.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] This property is common to both the zincblende and wurtzite crystal structures.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] To first order, there is only one independent piezoelectric coefficient in zincblende, called e14, coupled to shear components of the strain.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] In wurtzite, there are instead three independent piezoelectric coefficients: *e*31, *e*33 and *e*15.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The semiconductors where the strongest piezoelectricity is observed are those commonly found in the wurtzite structure, i.e.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] GaN, InN, AlN and ZnO (see piezotronics).
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Since 2006, there have also been a number of reports of strong non linear piezoelectric effects in polar semiconductors.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Such effects are generally recognized to be at least important if not of the same order of magnitude as the first order approximation.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The piezo-response of polymers is not as high as the response for ceramics; however, polymers hold properties that ceramics do not.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Over the last few decades, non-toxic, piezoelectric polymers have been studied and applied due to their flexibility and smaller acoustical impedance.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Other properties that make these materials significant include their biocompatibility, biodegradability, low cost, and low power consumption compared to other piezo-materials (ceramics, etc.).
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric polymers can be classified by bulk polymers, voided charged polymers ("piezoelectrets"), and polymer composites.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] A piezo-response observed by bulk polymers is mostly due to its molecular structure.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] There are two types of bulk polymers: amorphous and semi-crystalline.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Examples of semi-crystalline polymers are polyvinylidene fluoride (PVDF) and its copolymers, polyamides, and parylene-C.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Non-crystalline polymers, such as polyimide and polyvinylidene chloride (PVDC), fall under amorphous bulk polymers.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Voided charged polymers exhibit the piezoelectric effect due to charge induced by poling of a porous polymeric film.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Under an electric field, charges form on the surface of the voids forming dipoles.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Electric responses can be caused by any deformation of these voids.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect can also be observed in polymer composites by integrating piezoelectric ceramic particles into a polymer film.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] A polymer does not have to be piezo-active to be an effective material for a polymer composite.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] In this case, a material could be made up of an inert matrix with a separate piezo-active component.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] PVDF exhibits piezoelectricity several times greater than quartz.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The piezo-response observed from PVDF is about 20–30 pC/N.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] That is an order of 5–50 times less than that of piezoelectric ceramic lead zirconate titanate (PZT).
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The thermal stability of the piezoelectric effect of polymers in the PVDF family (i.e. vinylidene fluoride co-poly trifluoroethylene) goes up to 125 °C.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Some applications of PVDF are pressure sensors, hydrophones, and shock wave sensors.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Due to their flexibility, piezoelectric composites have been proposed as energy harvesters and nanogenerators.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] In 2018, it was reported by Zhu et al. that a piezoelectric response of about 17 pC/N could be obtained from PDMS/PZT nanocomposite at 60% porosity.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Another PDMS nanocomposite was reported in 2017, in which BaTiO3 was integrated into PDMS to make a stretchable, transparent nanogenerator for self-powered physiological monitoring.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] In 2016, polar molecules were introduced into a polyurethane foam in which high responses of up to 244 pC/N were reported.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Most materials exhibit at least weak piezoelectric responses.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Trivial examples include sucrose (table sugar), DNA, and viral proteins, including those from bacteriophage.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] An actuator based on wood fibers (cellulose fibers) has been reported.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] D33 responses for cellular polypropylene are around 200 pC/N.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Some applications of cellular polypropylene are musical key pads, microphones, and ultrasound-based echolocation systems.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Recently, a single amino acid, β-glycine, displayed a high piezoelectric response of 178 pm V−1 compared with other biological materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Ionic liquids were recently identified as the first piezoelectric liquid.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Direct piezoelectricity of some substances, like quartz, can generate potential differences of thousands of volts.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The principle of operation of a piezoelectric sensor is that a physical dimension, transformed into a force, acts on two opposing faces of the sensing element.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Depending on the design of a sensor, different "modes" to load the piezoelectric element can be used: longitudinal, transversal and shear.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Detection of pressure variations in the form of sound is the most common sensor application, e.g. piezoelectric microphones (sound waves bend the piezoelectric material, creating a changing voltage) and piezoelectric pickups for acoustic-electric guitars.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] A piezo sensor attached to the body of an instrument is known as a contact microphone.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric sensors especially are used with high frequency sound in ultrasonic transducers for medical imaging and also industrial nondestructive testing (NDT).
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] For many sensing techniques, the sensor can act as both a sensor and an actuator—often the term *transducer* is preferred when the device acts in this dual capacity, but most piezo devices have this property of reversibility whether it is used or not.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Ultrasonic transducers, for example, can inject ultrasound waves into the body, receive the returned wave, and convert it to an electrical signal (a voltage).
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Most medical ultrasound transducers are piezoelectric.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] As very high electric fields correspond to only tiny changes in the width of the crystal, this width can be changed with better-than-μm precision, making piezo crystals the most important tool for positioning objects with extreme accuracy—thus their use in actuators.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Multilayer ceramics, using layers thinner than 100 μm, allow reaching high electric fields with voltage lower than 150 V.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] These ceramics are used within two kinds of actuators: direct piezo actuators and amplified piezoelectric actuators.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] While direct actuator's stroke is generally lower than 100 μm, amplified piezo actuators can reach millimeter strokes.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectrical properties of quartz are useful as a standard of frequency.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Aside from the stepping stick-slip motor, all these motors work on the same principle.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Driven by dual orthogonal vibration modes with a phase difference of 90°, the contact point between two surfaces vibrates in an elliptical path, producing a frictional force between the surfaces.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Usually, one surface is fixed, causing the other to move.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] In most piezoelectric motors, the piezoelectric crystal is excited by a sine wave signal at the resonant frequency of the motor.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Using the resonance effect, a much lower voltage can be used to produce a high vibration amplitude.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] A stick-slip motor works using the inertia of a mass and the friction of a clamp.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Some are used for camera sensor displacement, thus allowing an anti-shake function.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Different teams of researchers have been investigating ways to reduce vibrations in materials by attaching piezo elements to the material.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] When the material is bent by a vibration in one direction, the vibration-reduction system responds to the bend and sends electric power to the piezo element to bend in the other direction.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Applications to flexible structures, such as shells and plates, have also been studied for nearly three decades.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Piezosurgery is a minimally invasive technique that aims to cut a target tissue with little damage to neighboring tissues.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] For example, Hoigne *et al.* uses frequencies in the range 25–29 kHz, causing microvibrations of 60–210 μm.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] It has the ability to cut mineralized tissue without cutting neurovascular tissue and other soft tissue, thereby maintaining a blood-free operating area, better visibility and greater precision.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] In 2019, Pernas-Salomón and Shmuel developed a dynamic homogenization method by which they were the first to show that piezoelectric composites exhibit an effective coupling between linear momentum and the electric field, which they termed electro-momentum coupling.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Because homogeneous piezoelectric materials do not exhibit this coupling, such composites belong to the class of metamaterials—artificial media engineered to display extraordinary effective properties, in magnitude or in kind.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Electro-momentum coupling is analogous to Willis coupling in elastic composites, which couples linear momentum to strain and was discovered by J.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] The local part of these couplings—like piezoelectric coupling—emerges from broken symmetries.
[src:ceramics-materials/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric metamaterials with electro-momentum coupling offer a mechanism for wave manipulation akin to Willis coupling: they impart a direction-dependent phase shift that enables wavefront shaping, with the added advantage of electrical tunability.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] In materials science, a **refractory** (or **refractory material**) is a material that is resistant to decomposition by heat or chemical attack and that retains its strength and rigidity at high temperatures.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] They are inorganic, non-metallic compounds that may be porous or non-porous, and their crystallinity varies widely: they may be crystalline, polycrystalline, amorphous, or composite.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] They are typically composed of oxides, carbides or nitrides of the following elements: silicon, aluminium, magnesium, calcium, boron, chromium and zirconium.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Many refractories are ceramics, but some such as graphite are not, and some ceramics such as clay pottery are not considered refractory.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Refractories are distinguished from the *refractory metals*, which are elemental metals and their alloys that have high melting temperatures.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Refractories are defined by ASTM C71 as "non-metallic materials having those chemical and physical properties that make them applicable for structures, or as components of systems, that are exposed to environments above 1,000 °F (811 K; 538 °C)".
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Refractory materials are used in furnaces, kilns, incinerators, and reactors.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Refractories are also used to make crucibles and molds for casting glass and metals.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] The iron and steel industry and metal casting sectors use approximately 70% of all refractories produced.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Refractory materials must be chemically and physically stable at high temperatures.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Depending on the operating environment, they must be resistant to thermal shock, be chemically inert, and/or have specific ranges of thermal conductivity and of the coefficient of thermal expansion.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] The oxides of aluminium (alumina), silicon (silica) and magnesium (magnesia) are the most important materials used in the manufacturing of refractories.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Another oxide usually found in refractories is the oxide of calcium (lime).
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Fire clays are also widely used in the manufacture of refractories.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Refractories must be chosen according to the conditions they face.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Some applications require special refractory materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Zirconia is used when the material must withstand extremely high temperatures.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Silicon carbide and carbon (graphite) are two other refractory materials used in some very severe temperature conditions, but they cannot be used in contact with oxygen, as they would oxidize and burn.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Binary compounds such as tungsten carbide or boron nitride can be very refractory.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Hafnium carbide is the most refractory binary compound known, with a melting point of 3890 °C.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] The ternary compound tantalum hafnium carbide has one of the highest melting points of all known compounds (4215 °C).
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Molybdenum disilicide has a high melting point of 2030 °C and is often used as a heating element.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Refractories have multiple useful applications.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] In the metallurgy industry, refractories are used for lining furnaces, kilns, reactors, and other vessels which hold and transport hot media such as metal and slag.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Refractories have other high temperature applications such as fired heaters, hydrogen reformers, ammonia primary and secondary reformers, cracking furnaces, utility boilers, catalytic cracking units, air heaters, and sulfur furnaces.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] They are used for surfacing flame deflectors in rocket launch structures.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Acidic refractories are generally impervious to acidic materials but easily attacked by basic materials, and are thus used with acidic slag in acidic environments.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] They include substances such as silica, alumina, and fire clay brick refractories.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Notable reagents that can attack both alumina and silica are hydrofluoric acid, phosphoric acid, and fluorinated gases (e.g.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] At high temperatures, acidic refractories may also react with limes and basic oxides.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Basic refractories are used in areas where slags and atmosphere are basic.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] They are stable to alkaline materials but can react to acids, which is important e. g. when removing phosphorus from pig iron (see Gilchrist–Thomas process).
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] The main raw materials belong to the RO group, of which magnesia (MgO) is a common example.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Other examples include dolomite and chrome-magnesia.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] For the first half of the twentieth century, the steel making process used artificial periclase (roasted magnesite) as a furnace lining material.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] These are used in areas where slags and atmosphere are either acidic or basic and are chemically stable to both acids and bases.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] The main raw materials belong to, but are not confined to, the R2O3 group.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Common examples of these materials are alumina (Al2O3), chromia (Cr2O3) and carbon.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Refractory objects are manufactured in standard shapes and special shapes.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Standard shapes have dimensions that conform to conventions used by refractory manufacturers and are generally applicable to kilns or furnaces of the same types.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Standard shapes are usually bricks that have a standard dimension of 9 in × 4.5 in × 2.5 in (229 mm × 114 mm × 64 mm) and this dimension is called a "one brick equivalent".
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] "Brick equivalents" are used in estimating how many refractory bricks it takes to make an installation into an industrial furnace.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] There are ranges of standard shapes of different sizes manufactured to produce walls, roofs, arches, tubes and circular apertures etc.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Special shapes are specifically made for specific locations within furnaces and for particular kilns or furnaces.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Special shapes are usually less dense and therefore less hard wearing than standard shapes.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] These are without prescribed form and are only given shape upon application.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] These types are known as monolithic refractories.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Common examples include plastic masses, ramming masses, castables, gunning masses, fettling mix, and mortars.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Dry vibration linings often used in induction furnace linings are also monolithic, and sold and transported as a dry powder, usually with a magnesia/alumina composition with additions of other chemicals for altering specific properties.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] They are also finding more applications in blast furnace linings, although this use is still rare.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Refractory materials are classified into three types based on fusion temperature (melting point).
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Refractoriness is the property of a refractory's multiphase to reach a specific softening degree at high temperature without load, and is measured with a pyrometric cone equivalent (PCE) test.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Refractories may be classified by thermal conductivity as either conducting, nonconducting, or insulating.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Examples of conducting refractories are silicon carbide (SiC) and zirconium carbide (ZrC), whereas examples of nonconducting refractories are silica and alumina.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Insulating refractories include calcium silicate materials, kaolin, and zirconia.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] Insulating refractories are used to reduce the rate of heat loss through furnace walls.
[src:ceramics-materials/refractory] These refractories have low thermal conductivity due to a high degree of porosity, with a desired porous structure of small, uniform pores evenly distributed throughout the refractory brick in order to minimize thermal conductivity.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Electronic applications of silicon carbide such as light-emitting diodes (LEDs) and detectors in early radios were first demonstrated around 1907.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide is used in semiconductor electronic devices that operate at high temperatures, high voltages or both.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Naturally occurring moissanite is found in only minute quantities in certain types of meteorite, corundum deposits and kimberlite.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Virtually all the silicon carbide sold in the world, including moissanite jewelry, is synthetic.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Natural moissanite was first found in 1893 as a small component of the Canyon Diablo meteorite in Arizona by Ferdinand Henri Moissan, after whom the material was named in 1905.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Moissan's discovery of naturally occurring SiC was initially disputed because his sample may have been contaminated by silicon carbide saw blades that were already on the market at that time.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] While rare on Earth, silicon carbide is remarkably common in space.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] It is a common form of star dust found around carbon-rich stars, and examples of this star dust have been found in pristine condition in primitive (unaltered) meteorites.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The silicon carbide found in space and meteorites is almost exclusively the beta-polymorph.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Analysis of SiC grains found in the Murchison meteorite, a carbonaceous chondrite meteorite, has revealed anomalous isotopic ratios of carbon and silicon, indicating that these grains originated outside the Solar System.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Wide-scale production is credited to Edward Goodrich Acheson in 1891.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Acheson was attempting to prepare artificial diamonds when he heated a mixture of clay (aluminium silicate) and powdered coke (carbon) in an iron bowl.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] He called the blue crystals that formed *carborundum*, believing it to be a new compound of carbon and aluminium, similar to corundum.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Henri Moissan also synthesized SiC by several routes, including dissolution of carbon in molten silicon, melting a mixture of calcium carbide and silica, and reducing silica with carbon in an electric furnace.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Acheson patented the method for making silicon carbide powder on February 28, 1893.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Acheson also developed the electric batch furnace by which SiC is still made today and formed the Carborundum Company to manufacture bulk SiC, initially for use as an abrasive.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In 1900 the company settled with the Electric Smelting and Aluminum Company when a judge's decision gave "priority broadly" to its founders "for reducing ores and other substances by the incandescent method".
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The first use of SiC was as an abrasive.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] This was followed by electronic applications.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In the beginning of the 20th century, silicon carbide was used as a detector in the first radios.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In 1907 Henry Joseph Round produced the first LED by applying a voltage to a SiC crystal and observing yellow, green and orange emission at the cathode.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The effect was later rediscovered by O.V.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Because natural moissanite is extremely scarce, most silicon carbide is synthetic.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide is used as an abrasive, as well as a semiconductor and diamond simulant of gem quality.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The simplest process to manufacture silicon carbide is to combine silica sand and carbon in an Acheson graphite electric resistance furnace at a high temperature, between 1,600 °C (2,910 °F) and 2,500 °C (4,530 °F).
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Fine SiO2 particles in plant material (e.g. rice husks) can be converted to SiC by heating in the excess carbon from the organic material.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The silica fume, which is a byproduct of producing elemental silicon and ferrosilicon alloys, can also be converted to SiC by heating with graphite at 1,500 °C (2,730 °F).
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The material formed in the Acheson furnace varies in purity, according to its distance from the graphite resistor heat source.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Colorless, pale yellow, and green crystals have the highest purity and are found closest to the resistor.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The color changes to blue and black at greater distance from the resistor, and these darker crystals are less pure.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Nitrogen and aluminium are common impurities, and they affect the electrical conductivity of SiC.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] This process yields high-quality single crystals, mostly of 6H-SiC phase (because of high growth temperature).
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] A modified Lely process involving induction heating in graphite crucibles yields even larger single crystals of 4 inches (10 cm) in diameter, having a section 81 times larger compared to the conventional Lely process.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide wafers are often grown using this method, known in the industry as physical vapor transport with a seed wafer made of SiC.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] SiC powder is heated until it sublimes, and then the SiC vapor cools and deposits below the seed crystal.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Cubic SiC is usually grown by the more expensive process of chemical vapor deposition (CVD) of silane, hydrogen, and nitrogen.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Homoepitaxial and heteroepitaxial SiC layers can be grown employing both gas and liquid phase approaches.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] To form complexly shaped SiC, preceramic polymers can be used as precursors which form the ceramic product through pyrolysis at temperatures in the range 1,000–1,100 °C.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Precursor materials to obtain silicon carbide in such a manner include polycarbosilanes, poly(methylsilyne) and polysilazanes.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide materials obtained through the pyrolysis of preceramic polymers are known as polymer derived ceramics or PDCs.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Pyrolysis of preceramic polymers is most often conducted under an inert atmosphere at relatively low temperatures.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Relative to the CVD process, the pyrolysis method is advantageous because the polymer can be formed into various shapes prior to thermalization into the ceramic.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] SiC can also be made into wafers by cutting a single crystal either using a diamond wire saw or by using a laser.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] SiC is a useful semiconductor used in power electronics.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide exists in about 250 crystalline forms.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Through inert atmospheric pyrolysis of preceramic polymers, silicon carbide in a glassy amorphous form is also produced.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The polymorphism of SiC is characterized by a large family of similar crystalline structures called polytypes.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] They are variations of the same chemical compound that are identical in two dimensions and differ in the third.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Thus, they can be viewed as layers stacked in a certain sequence.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Alpha silicon carbide (α-SiC) is the most commonly encountered polymorph, and is formed at temperatures greater than 1,700 °C and has a hexagonal crystal structure (similar to Wurtzite).
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The beta modification (β-SiC), with a zinc blende crystal structure (similar to diamond), is formed at temperatures below 1,700 °C.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Until recently, the beta form has had relatively few commercial uses, although there is now increasing interest in its use as a support for heterogeneous catalysts, owing to its higher surface area compared to the alpha form.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The brown to black color of the industrial product results from iron impurities.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The rainbow-like luster of the crystals is due to the thin-film interference of a passivation layer of silicon dioxide that forms on the surface.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The high sublimation temperature of SiC (approximately 2,700 °C) makes it useful for bearings and furnace parts.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide does not melt but begins to sublimate near 2,700 °C like graphite, having an appreciable vapor pressure near that temperature.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] It is also highly inert chemically, partly due to the formation of a thin passivated layer of SiO2.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] There is currently much interest in its use as a semiconductor material in electronics, where its high thermal conductivity, high electric field breakdown strength and high maximum current density make it more promising than silicon for high-powered devices.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] SiC has a very low coefficient of thermal expansion of about 2.3 × 10−6 K−1 near 300 K (for 4H and 6H SiC) and experiences no phase transitions in the temperature range 5 K to 340 K that would cause discontinuities in the thermal expansion coefficient.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide is a semiconductor, which can be doped n-type by nitrogen or phosphorus and p-type by beryllium, boron, aluminium, or gallium.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Metallic conductivity has been achieved by heavy doping with boron, aluminium, or nitrogen.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Superconductivity has been detected in 3C-SiC:Al, 3C-SiC:B and 6H-SiC:B at similar temperatures ~1.5 K.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] A crucial difference is however observed for the magnetic field behavior between aluminium and boron doping: 3C-SiC:Al is type-II.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In contrast, 3C-SiC:B is type-I, as is 6H-SiC:B.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Thus, the superconducting properties seem to depend more on dopant (B vs.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In an attempt to explain this dependence, it was noted that B substitutes at C sites in SiC, but Al substitutes at Si sites.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Therefore, Al and B "see" different environments, in both polytypes.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In manufacturing, it is used for its hardness in abrasive machining processes such as grinding, honing, water-jet cutting and sandblasting.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] SiC provides a much sharper and harder alternative for sand blasting as compared to aluminium oxide.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Particles of silicon carbide are laminated to paper to create sandpapers and the grip tape on skateboards.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In the arts, silicon carbide is a popular abrasive in modern lapidary due to the durability and low cost of the material.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In 1982, an exceptionally strong composite of aluminium oxide and silicon carbide whiskers was discovered.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Development of this laboratory-produced composite to a commercial product took only three years.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In 1985, the first commercial cutting tools made from this alumina and silicon carbide whisker-reinforced composite were introduced into the market.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In the 1980s and 1990s, silicon carbide was studied in several research programs for high-temperature gas turbines in Europe, Japan, and the United States.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The components were intended to replace nickel superalloy turbine blades or nozzle vanes.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] However, none of these projects resulted in a production quantity, mainly because of its low impact resistance and its low fracture toughness.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Like other hard ceramics (namely alumina and boron carbide), silicon carbide is used in composite armor (e.g.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Chobham armor), and in ceramic plates in bulletproof vests.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Dragon Skin, which was produced by Pinnacle Armor, used disks of silicon carbide.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Improved fracture toughness in SiC armor can be facilitated through the phenomenon of abnormal grain growth or AGG.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The growth of abnormally long silicon carbide grains may serve to impart a toughening effect through crack-wake bridging, similar to whisker reinforcement.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Similar AGG-toughening effects have been reported in silicon nitride (Si3N4).
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide is used as a support and shelving material in high-temperature kilns such as for firing ceramics, glass fusing, or glass casting.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] SiC kiln shelves are considerably lighter and more durable than traditional alumina shelves.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In December 2015, infusion of silicon carbide nano-particles in molten magnesium was mentioned as a way to produce a new strong and plastic alloy suitable for use in aeronautics, aerospace, automobile, and micro-electronics.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon-infiltrated carbon-carbon composite is used for high-performance "ceramic" brake discs, as they can withstand extreme temperatures.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The silicon reacts with the graphite in the carbon-carbon composite to become carbon-fiber-reinforced silicon carbide (C/SiC).
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] These brake discs are used on some road-going sports cars, supercars, as well as other performance cars including the Porsche Carrera GT, the Bugatti Veyron, the Chevrolet Corvette ZR1, the McLaren P1, Bentley, Ferrari, Lamborghini and some specific high-performance Audi cars.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide is also used in a sintered form for diesel particulate filters.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] It is also used as an oil additive to reduce friction, emissions, and harmonics.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] SiC is used in crucibles for holding melting metal in small and large foundry applications.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The earliest electrical application of SiC was as a surge protection in lightning arresters in electric power systems.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] These devices must exhibit high resistance until the voltage across them reaches a certain threshold VT at which point their resistance must drop to a lower level and maintain this level until the applied voltage drops below VT flushing current into the ground.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] It was recognized early on that SiC had such a voltage-dependent resistance, and so columns of SiC pellets were connected between high-voltage power lines and the earth.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] When a lightning strike to the line raises the line voltage sufficiently, the SiC column will conduct, allowing strike current to pass harmlessly to the earth instead of along the power line.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The SiC columns proved to conduct significantly at normal power-line operating voltages and thus had to be placed in series with a spark gap.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] This spark gap is ionized and rendered conductive when lightning raises the voltage of the power line conductor, thus effectively connecting the SiC column between the power conductor and the earth.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Spark gaps used in lightning arresters are unreliable, either failing to strike an arc when needed or failing to turn off afterwards, in the latter case due to material failure or contamination by dust or salt.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Usage of SiC columns was originally intended to eliminate the need for the spark gap in lightning arresters.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Gapped SiC arresters were used for lightning-protection and sold under the GE and Westinghouse brand names, among others.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The gapped SiC arrester has been largely displaced by no-gap varistors that use columns of zinc oxide pellets.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide was the first commercially important semiconductor material.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] A crystal radio "carborundum" (synthetic silicon carbide) detector diode was patented by Henry Harrison Chase Dunwoody in 1906.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] It found much early use in shipboard receivers.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In 1993, the silicon carbide was considered a semiconductor in both research and early mass production providing advantages for fast, high-temperature and/or high-voltage devices.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The first devices available were Schottky diodes, followed by junction-gate FETs and MOSFETs for high-power switching.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Bipolar transistors and thyristors were described.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] A major problem for SiC commercialization has been the elimination of defects: edge dislocations, screw dislocations (both hollow and closed core), triangular defects and basal plane dislocations.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] As a result, devices made of SiC crystals initially displayed poor reverse blocking performance, though researchers have been tentatively finding solutions to improve the breakdown performance.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Apart from crystal quality, problems with the interface of SiC with silicon dioxide have hampered the development of SiC-based power MOSFETs and insulated-gate bipolar transistors.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Although the mechanism is still unclear, nitriding has dramatically reduced the defects causing the interface problems.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In 2008, the first commercial JFETs rated at 1,200 V were introduced to the market, followed in 2011 by the first commercial MOSFETs rated at 1200 V.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] JFETs are now available rated 650 V to 1,700 V with resistance as low as 25 mΩ.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Beside SiC switches and SiC Schottky diodes (also Schottky barrier diode, SBD) in the popular TO-247 and TO-220 packages, companies started even earlier to implement the bare chips into their power electronic modules.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] SiC SBD diodes found wide market spread being used in PFC circuits and IGBT power modules.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Conferences such as the International Conference on Integrated Power Electronics Systems (CIPS) report regularly about the technological progress of SiC power devices.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Beginning with Tesla Model 3 the inverters in the drive unit use 24 pairs of silicon carbide (SiC) MOSFET chips rated for 650 volts each.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide in this instance gave Tesla a significant advantage over chips made of silicon in terms of size and weight.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] A number of automobile manufacturers are planning to incorporate silicon carbide into power electronic devices in their products.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] A significant increase in production of silicon carbide is projected, beginning with a large plant opened 2022 by Wolfspeed, in upstate New York.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The phenomenon of electroluminescence was discovered in 1907 using silicon carbide and some of the first commercial LEDs were based on this material.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] When General Electric of America introduced its SSL-1 Solid State Lamp in March 1967, using a tiny chip of semi-conducting SiC to emit a point of yellow light, it was then the world's brightest LED.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] By 1970 it had been usurped by brighter red LEDs, but yellow LEDs made from 3C-SiC continued to be manufactured in the Soviet Union in the 1970s and blue LEDs (6H-SiC) worldwide in the 1980s.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Carbide LED production soon stopped when a different material, gallium nitride, showed 10–100 times brighter emission.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] This difference in efficiency is due to the unfavorable indirect bandgap of SiC, whereas GaN has a direct bandgap which favors light emission.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] However, SiC is still one of the important LED components: It is a popular substrate for growing GaN devices, and it also serves as a heat spreader in high-power LEDs.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The low thermal expansion coefficient, high hardness, rigidity and thermal conductivity make silicon carbide a desirable mirror material for astronomical telescopes.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide fibers are used to measure gas temperatures in an optical technique called thin-filament pyrometry.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] It involves the placement of a thin filament in a hot gas stream.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Radiative emissions from the filament can be correlated with filament temperature.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Filaments are SiC fibers with a diameter of 15 micrometers, about one fifth that of a human hair.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Because the fibers are so thin, they do little to disturb the flame and their temperature remains close to that of the local gas.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Temperatures of about 800–2,500 K can be measured.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] References to silicon carbide heating elements exist from the early 20th century when they were produced by Acheson's Carborundum Co. in the U.S. and EKL in Berlin.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide offered increased operating temperatures compared with metallic heaters.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide elements are used today in the melting of glass and non-ferrous metal, heat treatment of metals, float glass production, production of ceramics and electronics components, igniters in pilot lights for gas heaters, etc.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The outer thermal protection layer of NASA's LOFTID inflatable heat shield incorporates a woven ceramic made from silicon carbide, with fiber of such small diameter that it can be bundled and spun into a yarn.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Due to SiC's exceptional neutron absorption capability, it is used as fuel cladding in nuclear reactors and as nuclear waste containment material.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] It is also used in producing radiation detectors for monitoring radiation levels in nuclear facilities, environmental monitoring, and medical imaging.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Again, SiC sensors and electronics for nuclear reactor applications are being developed potentially for future Martian nuclear power and the emerging terrestrial micro nuclear power plants.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide is an important material in TRISO-coated fuel particles, the type of nuclear fuel found in high temperature gas cooled reactors such as the pebble-bed reactor.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] A layer of silicon carbide gives coated fuel particles structural support and is the main diffusion barrier to the release of fission products.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide composite material has been investigated for use as a replacement for Zircaloy cladding in light water reactors.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] One of the reasons for this investigation is that, Zircaloy experiences hydrogen embrittlement as a consequence of the corrosion reaction with water.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] This produces a reduction in fracture toughness with increasing volumetric fraction of radial hydrides.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] This phenomenon increases drastically with increasing temperature to the detriment of the material.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide cladding does not experience this same mechanical degradation, but instead retains strength properties with increasing temperature.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The composite consists of SiC fibers wrapped around a SiC inner layer and surrounded by a SiC outer layer.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Problems have been reported with the ability to join the pieces of the SiC composite.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] As a gemstone used in jewelry, silicon carbide is called "synthetic moissanite" or just "moissanite" after the mineral name.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Moissanite is similar to diamond in several important respects: it is transparent and hard (9–9.5 on the Mohs scale, compared to 10 for diamond), with a refractive index between 2.65 and 2.69 (compared to 2.42 for diamond).
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Moissanite is somewhat harder than common cubic zirconia.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Unlike diamond, moissanite can be strongly birefringent.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] For this reason, moissanite jewels are cut along the optic axis of the crystal to minimize birefringent effects.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] 3.53 g/cm3), and much more resistant to heat than diamond.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] This results in a stone of higher luster, sharper facets, and good resilience.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Loose moissanite stones may be placed directly into wax ring moulds for lost-wax casting, as can diamond, as moissanite remains undamaged by temperatures up to 1,800 °C (3,270 °F).
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Moissanite has become popular as a diamond substitute, and may be misidentified as diamond, since its thermal conductivity is closer to diamond than any other substitute.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Many thermal diamond-testing devices cannot distinguish moissanite from diamond, but the gem is distinct in its birefringence and a very slight green or yellow fluorescence under ultraviolet light.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Some moissanite stones also have curved, string-like inclusions, which diamonds never have.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide, dissolved in a basic oxygen furnace used for making steel, acts as a fuel.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The additional energy liberated allows the furnace to process more scrap with the same charge of hot metal.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] It can also be used to raise tap temperatures and adjust the carbon and silicon content.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide is cheaper than a combination of ferrosilicon and carbon, produces cleaner steel and lower emissions due to low levels of trace elements, has a low gas content, and does not lower the temperature of steel.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The natural resistance to oxidation exhibited by silicon carbide, as well as the discovery of new ways to synthesize the cubic β-SiC form, with its larger surface area, has led to significant interest in its use as a heterogeneous catalyst support.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] This form has already been employed as a catalyst support for the oxidation of hydrocarbons, such as n-butane, to maleic anhydride.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide is used in carborundum printmaking – a collagraph printmaking technique.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Carborundum grit is applied in a paste to the surface of an aluminium plate.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] When the paste is dry, ink is applied and trapped in its granular surface, then wiped from the bare areas of the plate.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The ink plate is then printed onto paper in a rolling-bed press used for intaglio printmaking.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The result is a print of painted marks embossed into the paper.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Carborundum grit is also used in stone Lithography.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Its uniform particle size allows it to be used to "Grain" a stone which removes the previous image.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In a similar process to sanding, coarser grit Carborundum is applied to the stone and worked with a Levigator, typically a round plate eccentric on a perpendicular shaft, then gradually finer and finer grit is applied until the stone is clean.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] This creates a grease sensitive surface.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide can be used in the production of graphene because of its chemical properties that promote the production of graphene on the surface of SiC nanostructures.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] When it comes to its production, silicon is used primarily as a substrate to grow the graphene.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] But there are actually several methods that can be used to grow the graphene on the silicon carbide.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The confinement controlled sublimation (CCS) growth method consists of a SiC chip that is heated under vacuum with graphite.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Then the vacuum is released very gradually to control the growth of graphene.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] This method yields the highest quality graphene layers.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] But other methods have been reported to yield the same product as well.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Another way of growing graphene would be thermally decomposing SiC at a high temperature within a vacuum.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] But, this method turns out to yield graphene layers that contain smaller grains within the layers.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] So, there have been efforts to improve the quality and yield of graphene.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] One such method is to perform *ex situ* graphitization of silicon terminated SiC in an atmosphere consisting of argon.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] This method has proved to yield layers of graphene with larger domain sizes than the layer that would be attainable via other methods.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] This new method can be very viable to make higher quality graphene for a multitude of technological applications.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] When it comes to understanding how or when to use these methods of graphene production, most of them mainly produce or grow this graphene on the SiC within a growth enabling environment.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] It is utilized most often at rather higher temperatures (such as 1,300 °C) because of SiC thermal properties.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] However, there have been certain procedures that have been performed and studied that could potentially yield methods that use lower temperatures to help manufacture graphene.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] More specifically this different approach to graphene growth has been observed to produce graphene within a temperature environment of around 750 °C.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] This method entails the combination of certain methods like chemical vapor deposition (CVD) and surface segregation.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] And when it comes to the substrate, the procedure would consist of coating a SiC substrate with thin films of a transition metal.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] And after the rapid heat treating of this substance, the carbon atoms would then become more abundant at the surface interface of the transition metal film which would then yield graphene.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] And this process was found to yield graphene layers that were more continuous throughout the substrate surface.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide can host point defects in the crystal lattice, which are known as color centers.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] These defects can produce single photons on demand and thus serve as a platform for single-photon source.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Such a device is a fundamental resource for many emerging applications of quantum information science.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] If one pumps a color center via an external optical source or electric current, the color center will be brought to the excited state and then relax with the emission of one photon.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] One well known point defect in silicon carbide is the divacancy which has a similar electronic structure as the nitrogen-vacancy center in diamond.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] In 4H-SiC, the divacancy has four different configurations which correspond to four zero-phonon lines (ZPL).
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide is used in the manufacturing of fishing guides because of its durability and wear resistance.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide rings are fitted into a guide frame, typically made from stainless steel or titanium which keep the line from touching the rod blank.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] The rings provide a low friction surface which improves casting distance while providing adequate hardness that prevents abrasion from braided fishing line.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] Silicon carbide is used as a raw ingredient in some glazes applied to ceramics.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] At high temperatures it can reduce metal oxides forming silica and carbon dioxide.
[src:ceramics-materials/silicon-carbide] This can be used to make the glaze foam and crater due to the evolved carbon dioxide gas, or to reduce the colorant oxides and achieve colors such as copper reds otherwise only possible in a fuel powered reduction firing in an electric kiln.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Since the sintering temperature does not have to reach the melting point of the material, sintering is often chosen as the shaping process for materials with extremely high melting points, such as tungsten and molybdenum.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The study of sintering in metallurgical powder-related processes is known as powder metallurgy.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] An example of sintering can be observed when ice cubes in a glass of water adhere to each other, which is driven by the temperature difference between the water and the ice.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Examples of pressure-driven sintering are the compacting of snowfall to a glacier, and the formation of a hard snowball by pressing loose snow together.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The material produced by sintering is called *sinter*.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The word *sinter* comes from the Middle High German *sinter*, a cognate of English *cinder*.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering is generally considered successful when the process reduces porosity and enhances properties such as strength, electrical conductivity, translucency and thermal conductivity.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In some special cases, sintering is carefully applied to enhance the strength of a material while preserving porosity (like in filters or catalysts, where gas adsorption is a priority).
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] During the sintering process, atomic diffusion drives powder surface elimination in different stages, starting at the formation of necks between powders to final elimination of small pores at the end of the process.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The driving force for densification is the change in free energy from the decrease in surface area and lowering of the surface free energy by the replacement of solid-vapor interfaces.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] It forms new but lower-energy solid-solid interfaces with a net decrease in total free energy.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] On a microscopic scale, material transfer is affected by the change in pressure and differences in free energy across the curved surface.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] If the size of the particle is small (and its curvature is high), these effects become very large in magnitude.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The change in energy is much higher when the radius of curvature is less than a few micrometers, which is one of the main reasons why much ceramic technology is based on the use of fine-particle materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The ratio of bond area to particle size is a determining factor for properties such as strength and electrical conductivity.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] To yield the desired bond area, temperature and initial grain size are precisely controlled over the sintering process.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] At steady state, the particle radius and the vapor pressure are proportional to (p0)2/3 and to (p0)1/3, respectively.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The source of power for solid-state processes is the change in free or chemical potential energy between the neck and the surface of the particle.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This energy creates a transfer of material through the fastest means possible; if transfer were to take place from the particle volume or the grain boundary between particles, particle count would decrease and pores would be destroyed.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Pore elimination is fastest in samples with many pores of uniform size because the boundary diffusion distance is smallest.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] During the latter portions of the process, boundary and lattice diffusion from the boundary become important.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Control of temperature is very important to the sintering process, since grain-boundary diffusion and volume diffusion rely heavily upon temperature, particle size, particle distribution, material composition, and often other properties of the sintering environment itself.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering is part of the firing process used in the manufacture of pottery and other ceramic objects.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering and vitrification (which requires higher temperatures) are the two main mechanisms behind the strength and stability of ceramics.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintered ceramic objects are made from substances such as glass, alumina, zirconia, silica, magnesia, lime, beryllium oxide, and ferric oxide.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Some ceramic raw materials have a lower affinity for water and a lower plasticity index than clay, requiring organic additives in the stages before sintering.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering begins when sufficient temperatures have been reached to mobilize the active elements in the ceramic material, which can start below their melting point (typically at 50–80% of their melting point), e.g. as premelting.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] When sufficient sintering has taken place, the ceramic body will no longer break down in water; additional sintering can reduce the porosity of the ceramic, increase the bond area between ceramic particles, and increase the material strength.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In fact, sinterisation is associated with a remarkable shrinkage of the material because glass phases flow once their transition temperature is reached, and start consolidating the powdery structure and considerably reducing the porosity of the material.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering is performed at high temperature.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Additionally, a second and/or third external force (such as pressure, electric current) could be used.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] A commonly used second external force is pressure.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering performed by only heating is generally termed "pressureless sintering", which is possible with graded metal-ceramic composites, utilising a nanoparticle sintering aid and bulk molding technology.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] A variant used for 3D shapes is called hot isostatic pressing.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] To allow efficient stacking of product in the furnace during sintering and to prevent parts sticking together, many manufacturers separate ware using ceramic powder separator sheets.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] These sheets are available in various materials such as alumina, zirconia and magnesia.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] They are additionally categorized by fine, medium and coarse particle sizes.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] By matching the material and particle size to the ware being sintered, surface damage and contamination can be reduced while maximizing furnace loading.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Most metals can be sintered, although some with greater difficulty (i.e., aluminium alloy and titanium alloys).
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This applies especially to pure metals produced in vacuum which suffer no surface contamination.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering under atmospheric pressure requires the use of a protective gas, quite often endothermic gas.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering, with subsequent reworking, can produce a great range of material properties.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Changes in density, alloying, and heat treatments can alter the physical characteristics of various products.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] $E_{n}/E=(D/d)^{3.4}$ where *D* is the density, *E* is Young's modulus and *d* is the maximum density of iron.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering is static when a metal powder under certain external conditions may exhibit coalescence, and yet reverts to its normal behavior when such conditions are removed.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In most cases, the density of a collection of grains increases as material flows into voids, causing a decrease in overall volume.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Mass movements that occur during sintering consist of the reduction of total porosity by repacking, followed by material transport due to evaporation and condensation from diffusion.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In the final stages, metal atoms move along crystal boundaries to the walls of internal pores, redistributing mass from the internal bulk of the object and smoothing pore walls.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Surface tension is the driving force for this movement.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] A special form of sintering (which is still considered part of powder metallurgy) is liquid-state sintering in which at least one but not all elements are in a liquid state.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Liquid-state sintering is required for making cemented carbide and tungsten carbide.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintered bronze in particular is frequently used as a material for bearings, since its porosity allows lubricants to flow through it or remain captured within it.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintered copper may be used as a wicking structure in certain types of heat pipe construction, where the porosity allows a liquid agent to move through the porous material via capillary action.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] For materials that have high melting points such as molybdenum, tungsten, rhenium, tantalum, osmium and carbon, sintering is one of the few viable manufacturing processes.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In these cases, very low porosity is desirable and can often be achieved.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintered metal powder is used to make frangible shotgun shells called breaching rounds, as used by military and SWAT teams to quickly force entry into a locked room.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] These shotgun shells are designed to destroy door deadbolts, locks and hinges without risking lives by ricocheting or by flying on at lethal speed through the door.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] They work by destroying the object they hit and then dispersing into a relatively harmless powder.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintered bronze and stainless steel are used as filter materials in applications requiring high temperature resistance while retaining the ability to regenerate the filter element.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] For example, sintered stainless steel elements are employed for filtering steam in food and pharmaceutical applications, and sintered bronze in aircraft hydraulic systems.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering of powders containing precious metals such as silver and gold is used to make small jewelry items.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Evaporative self-assembly of colloidal silver nanocubes into supercrystals has been shown to allow the sintering of electrical joints at temperatures lower than 200 °C.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Capability to produce materials of controlled, uniform porosity.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Capability to produce nearly net-shaped objects.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Capability to produce materials which cannot be produced by any other technology.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Capability to fabricate high-strength material like turbine blades.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] After sintering the mechanical strength to handling becomes higher.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The literature contains many references on sintering dissimilar materials to produce solid/solid-phase compounds or solid/melt mixtures at the processing stage.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Almost any substance can be obtained in powder form, through either chemical, mechanical or physical processes, so basically any material can be obtained through sintering.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] When pure elements are sintered, the leftover powder is still pure, so it can be recycled.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Plastic materials are formed by sintering for applications that require materials of specific porosity.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintered plastic porous components are used in filtration and to control fluid and gas flows.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintered plastics are used in applications requiring caustic fluid separation processes such as the nibs in whiteboard markers, inhaler filters, and vents for caps and liners on packaging materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintered ultra high molecular weight polyethylene materials are used as ski and snowboard base materials.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The porous texture allows wax to be retained within the structure of the base material, thus providing a more durable wax coating.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] For materials that are difficult to sinter, a process called liquid phase sintering is commonly used.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Materials for which liquid phase sintering is common are Si3N4, WC, SiC, and more.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Liquid phase sintering is the process of adding an additive to the powder which will melt before the matrix phase.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] For liquid phase sintering to be practical the major phase should be at least slightly soluble in the liquid phase and the additive should melt before any major sintering of the solid particulate network occurs, otherwise rearrangement of grains will not occur.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Liquid phase sintering was successfully applied to improve grain growth of thin semiconductor layers from nanoparticle precursor films.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] These techniques employ electric currents to drive or enhance sintering.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Bloxam registered in 1906 the first patent on sintering powders using direct current in vacuum.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The primary purpose of his inventions was the industrial scale production of filaments for incandescent lamps by compacting tungsten or molybdenum particles.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The applied current was particularly effective in reducing surface oxides that increased the emissivity of the filaments.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In 1913, Weintraub and Rush patented a modified sintering method which combined electric current with pressure.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The benefits of this method were proved for the sintering of refractory metals as well as conductive carbide or nitride powders.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The starting boron–carbon or silicon–carbon powders were placed in an electrically insulating tube and compressed by two rods which also served as electrodes for the current.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The estimated sintering temperature was 2000 °C.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In the United States, sintering was first patented by Duval d'Adrian in 1922.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] His three-step process aimed at producing heat-resistant blocks from such oxide materials as zirconia, thoria or tantalia.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The steps were: (i) molding the powder; (ii) annealing it at about 2500 °C to make it conducting; (iii) applying current-pressure sintering as in the method by Weintraub and Rush.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering that uses an arc produced via a capacitance discharge to eliminate oxides before direct current heating, was patented by G.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This originated sintering methods employing pulsed or alternating current, eventually superimposed to a direct current.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Those techniques have been developed over many decades and summarized in more than 640 patents.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Of these technologies the most well known is resistance sintering (also called hot pressing) and spark plasma sintering, while electro sinter forging is the latest advancement in this field.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In spark plasma sintering (SPS), external pressure and an electric field are applied simultaneously to enhance the densification of the metallic/ceramic powder compacts.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] However, after commercialization it was determined there is no plasma, so the proper name is spark sintering as coined by Lenel.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The electric field driven densification supplements sintering with a form of hot pressing, to enable lower temperatures and taking less time than typical sintering.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] For a number of years, it was speculated that the existence of sparks or plasma between particles could aid sintering; however, Hulbert and coworkers systematically proved that the electric parameters used during spark plasma sintering make it (highly) unlikely.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In light of this, the name "spark plasma sintering" has been rendered obsolete.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Terms such as field assisted sintering technique (FAST), electric field assisted sintering (EFAS), and direct current sintering (DCS) have been implemented by the sintering community.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Using a direct current (DC) pulse as the electric current, spark plasma, spark impact pressure, joule heating, and an electrical field diffusion effect would be created.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] By modifying the graphite die design and its assembly, it is possible to perform pressureless sintering in spark plasma sintering facility.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This modified die design setup is reported to synergize the advantages of both conventional pressureless sintering and spark plasma sintering techniques.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Electro sinter forging is an electric current assisted sintering (ECAS) technology originated from capacitor discharge sintering.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] It is used for the production of diamond metal matrix composites and is under evaluation for the production of hard metals, nitinol and other metals and intermetallics.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] It is characterized by a very low sintering time, allowing machines to sinter at the same speed as a compaction press.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Pressureless sintering is the sintering of a powder compact (sometimes at very high temperatures, depending on the powder) without applied pressure.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This avoids density variations in the final component, which occurs with more traditional hot pressing methods.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The powder compact (if a ceramic) can be created by slip casting, injection moulding, and cold isostatic pressing.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] After presintering, the final green compact can be machined to its final shape before being sintered.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Three different heating schedules can be performed with pressureless sintering: constant-rate of heating (CRH), rate-controlled sintering (RCS), and two-step sintering (TSS).
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The microstructure and grain size of the ceramics may vary depending on the material and method used.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Constant-rate of heating (CRH), also known as temperature-controlled sintering, consists of heating the green compact at a constant rate up to the sintering temperature.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Experiments with zirconia have been performed to optimize the sintering temperature and sintering rate for CRH method.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Results showed that the grain sizes were identical when the samples were sintered to the same density, proving that grain size is a function of specimen density rather than CRH temperature mode.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In rate-controlled sintering (RCS), the densification rate in the open-porosity phase is lower than in the CRH method.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] By definition, the relative density, ρrel, in the open-porosity phase is lower than 90%.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Although this should prevent separation of pores from grain boundaries, it has been proven statistically that RCS did not produce smaller grain sizes than CRH for alumina, zirconia, and ceria samples.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Two-step sintering (TSS) uses two different sintering temperatures.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The first sintering temperature should guarantee a relative density higher than 75% of theoretical sample density.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This will remove supercritical pores from the body.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The sample will then be cooled down and held at the second sintering temperature until densification is completed.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Grains of cubic zirconia and cubic strontium titanate were significantly refined by TSS compared to CRH.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] However, the grain size changes in other ceramic materials, like tetragonal zirconia and hexagonal alumina, were not statistically significant.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In microwave sintering, heat is sometimes generated internally within the material, rather than via surface radiative heat transfer from an external heat source.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Some materials fail to couple and others exhibit run-away behavior, so it is restricted in usefulness.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] A benefit of microwave sintering is faster heating for small loads, meaning less time is needed to reach the sintering temperature, less heating energy is required and there are improvements in the product properties.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] A failing of microwave sintering is that it generally sinters only one compact at a time, so overall productivity turns out to be poor except for situations involving one of a kind sintering, such as for artists.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] As microwaves can only penetrate a short distance in materials with a high conductivity and a high permeability, microwave sintering requires the sample to be delivered in powders with a particle size around the penetration depth of microwaves in the particular material.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The sintering process and side-reactions run several times faster during microwave sintering at the same temperature, which results in different properties for the sintered product.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This technique is acknowledged to be quite effective in maintaining fine grains/nano sized grains in sintered bioceramics.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Magnesium phosphates and calcium phosphates are the examples which have been processed through the microwave sintering technique.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering in practice is the control of both densification and grain growth.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Densification is the act of reducing porosity in a sample, thereby making it denser.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Grain growth is the process of grain boundary motion and Ostwald ripening to increase the average grain size.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Many properties (mechanical strength, electrical breakdown strength, etc.) benefit from both a high relative density and a small grain size.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Therefore, being able to control these properties during processing is of high technical importance.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Since densification of powders requires high temperatures, grain growth naturally occurs during sintering.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Reduction of this process is key for many engineering ceramics.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Under certain conditions of chemistry and orientation, some grains may grow rapidly at the expense of their neighbours during sintering.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This phenomenon, known as abnormal grain growth (AGG), results in a bimodal grain size distribution that has consequences for the mechanical, dielectric and thermal performance of the sintered material.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] For densification to occur at a quick pace it is essential to have (1) an amount of liquid phase that is large in size, (2) a near complete solubility of the solid in the liquid, and (3) wetting of the solid by the liquid.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The power behind the densification is derived from the capillary pressure of the liquid phase located between the fine solid particles.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] When the liquid phase wets the solid particles, each space between the particles becomes a capillary in which a substantial capillary pressure is developed.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Densification requires constant capillary pressure where just solution-precipitation material transfer would not produce densification.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] For further densification, additional particle movement while the particle undergoes grain-growth and grain-shape changes occurs.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Shrinkage would result when the liquid slips between particles and increases pressure at points of contact causing the material to move away from the contact areas, forcing particle centers to draw near each other.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The sintering of liquid-phase materials involves a fine-grained solid phase to create the needed capillary pressures proportional to its diameter, and the liquid concentration must also create the required capillary pressure within range, else the process ceases.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The vitrification rate is dependent upon the pore size, the viscosity and amount of liquid phase present leading to the viscosity of the overall composition, and the surface tension.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Temperature dependence for densification controls the process because at higher temperatures viscosity decreases and increases liquid content.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Therefore, when changes to the composition and processing are made, it will affect the vitrification process.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering occurs by diffusion of atoms through the microstructure.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This diffusion is caused by a gradient of chemical potential – atoms move from an area of higher chemical potential to an area of lower chemical potential.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The different paths the atoms take to get from one spot to another are the "sintering mechanisms" or "matter transport mechanisms".
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] 6. plastic deformation – dislocation motion causes flow of matter.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Mechanisms 1–3 above are non-densifying (i.e. do not cause the pores and the overall ceramic body to shrink) but can still increase the area of the bond or "neck" between grains; they take atoms from the surface and rearrange them onto another surface or part of the same surface.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Mechanisms 4–6 are densifying – atoms are moved from the bulk material or the grain boundaries to the surface of pores, thereby eliminating porosity and increasing the density of the sample.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] A grain boundary (GB) is the transition area or interface between adjacent crystallites (or grains) of the same chemical and lattice composition, not to be confused with a phase boundary.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The adjacent grains do not have the same orientation of the lattice, thus giving the atoms in GB shifted positions relative to the lattice in the crystals.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Due to the shifted positioning of the atoms in the GB they have a higher energy state when compared with the atoms in the crystal lattice of the grains.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] It is this imperfection that makes it possible to selectively etch the GBs when one wants the microstructure to be visible.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Striving to minimize its energy leads to the coarsening of the microstructure to reach a metastable state within the specimen.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This involves minimizing its GB area and changing its topological structure to minimize its energy.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This grain growth can either be normal or abnormal, a normal grain growth is characterized by the uniform growth and size of all the grains in the specimen.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Abnormal grain growth is when a few grains grow much larger than the remaining majority.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The atoms in the GB are normally in a higher energy state than their equivalent in the bulk material.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This is due to their more stretched bonds, which gives rise to a GB tension $\sigma _{GB}$ .
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This extra energy that the atoms possess is called the grain boundary energy, $\gamma _{GB}$ .
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The grain will want to minimize this extra energy, thus striving to make the grain boundary area smaller and this change requires energy.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] "Or, in other words, a force has to be applied, in the plane of the grain boundary and acting along a line in the grain-boundary area, in order to extend the grain-boundary area in the direction of the force.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The force per unit length, i.e. tension/stress, along the line mentioned is σGB.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The GB tension can also be thought of as the attractive forces between the atoms at the surface and the tension between these atoms is due to the fact that there is a larger interatomic distance between them at the surface compared to the bulk (i.e. surface tension).
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] When the surface area becomes bigger the bonds stretch more and the GB tension increases.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] To counteract this increase in tension there must be a transport of atoms to the surface keeping the GB tension constant.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This diffusion of atoms accounts for the constant surface tension in liquids.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] For solids, on the other hand, diffusion of atoms to the surface might not be sufficient and the surface tension can vary with an increase in surface area.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] $\sigma _{GB}$ is normally expressed in units of ${\frac {N}{m}}$ while $\gamma _{GB}$ is normally expressed in units of ${\frac {J}{m^{2}}}$ $(J=Nm)$ since they are different physical properties.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In a two-dimensional isotropic material the grain boundary tension would be the same for the grains.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This would give angle of 120° at GB junction where three grains meet.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This would give the structure a hexagonal pattern which is the metastable state (or mechanical equilibrium) of the 2D specimen.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] A consequence of this is that, to keep trying to be as close to the equilibrium as possible, grains with fewer sides than six will bend the GB to try keep the 120° angle between each other.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This results in a curved boundary with its curvature towards itself.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] A grain with six sides will, as mentioned, have straight boundaries, while a grain with more than six sides will have curved boundaries with its curvature away from itself.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] A grain with six boundaries (i.e. hexagonal structure) is in a metastable state (i.e. local equilibrium) within the 2D structure.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In three dimensions structural details are similar but much more complex and the metastable structure for a grain is a non-regular 14-sided polyhedra with doubly curved faces.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In practice all arrays of grains are always unstable and thus always grow until prevented by a counterforce.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Grains strive to minimize their energy, and a curved boundary has a higher energy than a straight boundary.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This means that the grain boundary will migrate towards the curvature.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The consequence of this is that grains with less than 6 sides will decrease in size while grains with more than 6 sides will increase in size.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Grain growth occurs due to motion of atoms across a grain boundary.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Convex surfaces have a higher chemical potential than concave surfaces, therefore grain boundaries will move toward their center of curvature.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] As smaller particles tend to have a higher radius of curvature and this results in smaller grains losing atoms to larger grains and shrinking.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This is a process called Ostwald ripening.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Large grains grow at the expense of small grains.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Here *Q* is the molar activation energy, *R* is the ideal gas constant, *T* is absolute temperature, and *K0* is a material dependent factor.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] In most materials the sintered grain size is proportional to the inverse square root of the fractional porosity, implying that pores are the most effective retardant for grain growth during sintering.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] If a dopant is added to the material (example: Nd in BaTiO3) the impurity will tend to stick to the grain boundaries.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] As the grain boundary tries to move (as atoms jump from the convex to concave surface) the change in concentration of the dopant at the grain boundary will impose a drag on the boundary.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] The original concentration of solute around the grain boundary will be asymmetrical in most cases.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] As the grain boundary tries to move, the concentration on the side opposite of motion will have a higher concentration and therefore have a higher chemical potential.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This increased chemical potential will act as a backforce to the original chemical potential gradient that is the reason for grain boundary movement.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This decrease in net chemical potential will decrease the grain boundary velocity and therefore grain growth.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] If particles of a second phase which are insoluble in the matrix phase are added to the powder in the form of a much finer powder, then this will decrease grain boundary movement.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] When the grain boundary tries to move past the inclusion diffusion of atoms from one grain to the other, it will be hindered by the insoluble particle.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] This is because it is beneficial for particles to reside in the grain boundaries and they exert a force in opposite direction compared to grain boundary migration.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] A boundary of unit area will intersect all particles within a volume of 2r which is 2Nr particles.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Now, assuming that the grains only grow due to the influence of curvature, the driving force of growth is ${\frac {2\lambda }{R}}$ where (for homogeneous grain structure) R approximates to the mean diameter of the grains.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] so the critical diameter of the grains is dependent on the size and volume fraction of the particles at the grain boundaries.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] More complicated interactions which slow grain boundary motion include interactions of the surface energies of the two grains and the inclusion and are discussed in detail by C.S.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering is an important cause for loss of catalytic activity, especially on supported metal catalysts.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] It decreases the surface area of the catalyst and changes the surface structure.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] For a porous catalytic surface, the pores may collapse due to sintering, resulting in loss of surface area.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Sintering is in general an irreversible process.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Small catalyst particles have the highest possible relative surface area and high reaction temperature, both factors that generally increase the reactivity of a catalyst.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] However, these factors are also the circumstances under which sintering occurs.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Specific materials may also increase the rate of sintering.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] On the other hand, by alloying catalysts with other materials, sintering can be reduced.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Rare-earth metals in particular have been shown to reduce sintering of metal catalysts when alloyed.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] For many supported metal catalysts, sintering starts to become a significant effect at temperatures over 500 °C (932 °F).
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] Catalysts that operate at higher temperatures, such as a car catalyst, use structural improvements to reduce or prevent sintering.
[src:ceramics-materials/sintering] These improvements are in general in the form of a support made from an inert and thermally stable material such as silica, carbon or alumina.
